I had burning at the injection site 20 minutes after administration, but no concerns since I?ve had many vaccines before with no adverse reaction. At 35 minutes after the injection, I suddenly felt an intense deep aching pain in my left arm. Seconds after feeling the pain my heart fluttered. My palms and body began to sweat. The heart flutter made me stagger and feel off balance. I had another heart flutter. After that my vision closed in. I lost all depth perception. The next thing I knew I was on the floor. My wife caught me on my fall, so I didn't hit my head. She also called 911 and kept me talking to remain alert, but I was having a hard time focusing on anything but my breathing. When I became aware of my surroundings again, I had to concentrate hard on my breathing to remain conscious. My left arm all the way from my shoulder down to my fingertips was painful to the point of being unable to make a fist or support any of my body weight on it. The EMT/ ambulance showed up at 1:43pm. I was then transported to the emergency room, where I was checked in at 2:19pm. At 5:31pm I began getting what felt like a hot poker in my heart on the left side of my chest and some dizziness while sitting down. I was discharged at 7:30pm.  Since then, I have had one episode where I was standing and became as dizzy as when I first passed out. I got sweaty and my heart started racing, but I didn?t have any flutters. It eventually passed when I focused on my breathing. I have been extremely tired and unable to do any gentle activities, including standing and walking around the house without the potential of becoming lightheaded and dizzy.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Roughly a month after receiving the 2nd Pfizer COVID-19 dose (4/13/21), I started experiencing irregular menses. This was significant, as I am on the Nexplanon birth control implant, and have been for 4 years. During those 4 years, I have had essentially no periods, with some very irregular light spotting (roughly 1-3 days a year). Since June 2021, however, I started spotting for multiple days, and experiencing bleeding that seemed to be menses. The timing, however, was irregular. For example, I would bleed for 6 days with a normal menses flow, and then 9 days later, I experiences 4 days of light bleeding/spotting. Then 8 days later, I experienced two days of spotting. Then I experienced nothing for 3 weeks, after which I experienced 15 days of spotting/bleeding. I sought out medical attention in early July.
LAB_DATA: I went to my OBGYN in early July, after experiencing bleeding for the first time in 4 years despite still being on the Nexplanon implant. She advised me to see if the irregular bleeding continued over the next 1-2 months. She also ordered a transvaginal ultrasound if I experience continued irregularity to rule out anything serious.  After experiencing irregular menses in July and August, I scheduled a transvaginal ultrasound mid-August. The ultrasound didn't reveal anything serious. I had a follow up with my OBGYN on 1 September, during which she prescribed a course of Ibuprofen to see if anti-inflammatory medication would help.  I did a course of the Ibruprofen and still experience bleeding and some irregularity. I was advised that I could request additional birth control pills to try to reset my menses. I have not yet explored this option.  My menses are not painful, though I do experience PMS, i.e. swelling of breasts, tenderness, acne breakouts, and fatigue. I can live with having a period again, but it is a significant change, after 4 years of no period.
OTHER_MEDS: Flonase, Allegra. Nexplanon birth control implant, Vitamin D, Vitamin B-12

I started with a tingling in my left arm, which lasted about a month and then turned into severe pain. Later the pain disappeared but moved to the left arm, after about 2 weeks the pain in the arm stopped but moved to the upper back where it lasted about 3 weeks and after which the pain returned to the arms. At that time, my left buttock began to hurt simultaneously, then it spread to the thigh of my left leg. I have received physiotherapy, treatment only with heat because with the cold the pain became more intense. I have received massages, rubs with ointments and done exercises guided by the Physiotherapist. None of that worked and I stopped after about a month because the manipulation aggravated the pain. I went to a pain management doctor, who had to inject the painful area on my left buttock. Only the injection has relieved the pain in the left buttock a lot, but it still does not go away completely, still being of moderate intensity only in the presence of certain movements. Today, 10 months after these symptoms began, the pain has been decreasing. I no longer have pain in my upper back, but there is still a slight pain in both arms. The pain in the left buttock still persists, it is not permanent but it is moderate with many movements (such as lifting the leg for example to climb stairs). I have also noticed a tendency to cramp my arms, hands and legs with an ease and frequency that I did not have before.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 5:00 a.m., about 20 hours after receiving my vaccines, I was awakened from sleep by a strong hot flash and a very fast supraventricular tachycardia.  Note that I am prone to SVT due to mitral valve prolapse, but I do not normally have hot flashes in general, and do not nor do I normally have hot flashes when I have SVT.  The SVT was also faster than what I normally have.  For about 15 minutes I attempted vagal maneuvers (coughing), slow breathing and relaxation, and splashing cold water on my face, to no avail.  At that point I took 50 mg Atenolol and returned to slow breathing and relaxation, and within about another 15 minutes the SVT had stopped and the hot flash had lessened significantly (but did not completely go away).  Today I feel fine other than being tired (from interrupted sleep) and still having slight hot flash.  I took my temperature and it is very slightly elevated (98.8 F) from my normal (around 98.2 F).  I have not previously had any side effects from a seasonal flu vaccine, which I have been receiving for many years.  I did not previously have any side effects from either of my two doses of Covid19 vaccine.  While an unpleasant episode, even if I had known beforehand that it would happen, it would not have stopped me from getting my vaccines.  Thank you.
HISTORY: Hypothyroidism, hypertension, mitral valve prolapse (symptomatic with PVCs and SVT)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received booster on Sunday, 10/3 at 3:00 PM (3rd dose), by Monday at 2:00 AM began to feel normal symptoms such as nausea, headache, dizziness, but by Tuesday, 10/5 at 10 PM had significant stomach pains at a 10 out of 10  (similar to feeling food poisoning). I also had chest pain. I felt dizzy and lightheaded as well.  I then began to have violent diarrhea that would not stop (15+ times per day) and ended up in the emergency room on Thursday, 10/7, where I received fluids, and they monitored my heart. I was still having diarrhea at that time. They saw on EKG that I now had Long QT (at 500), which I've only had in the past secondary to medication.  I did not have Long QT again prior to this event as I had an EKG in May 2021 and it did not show Long QT.  They also tested me for everything including my fecal, COVID PCR test, influenza A, B, and all was negative. The ER doctor informed me that he thought it was related to the vaccine. I'm filing this report to make others aware that this could potentially happen, and there could be an impact on the QT/QTC for the heart.
LAB_DATA: ECG while in ER at Clinic Hospital on 10/7 GIPA Screen Culture 10/5 at hospital on 10/7 Bacterial Eneteric Pathogens PCR at hospital 10/7 Influenza A,B/SARS CoV-2, PCR at hospital 10/7 Complete Blood Count at hospital 10/7 Metabolic/Electrolyte Panel at hospital 10/7 Liver Function Panel at hospital 10/7 Lactic Acid Level at hospital 10/7 Lipase Level at hospital 10/7 Troponin T at hospital 10/7 Nucleated RBC at hospital 10/7

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the seasonal flu vaccination from her school on January 5, 2021 at the facility. Approximately 2.5 weeks later consistent headache was noted by patient as she resumed her day to day activities and career as a preschool teacher. On January 25, patient reported a tingling sensation in her face followed by repetitive nose flaring and scrunching. Symptoms proceeded to raising of the upper lip bilaterally, right greater than left. Symptoms then progressed to seizure/tic like symptoms, convulsing and shaking of her entire body bilaterally without loss of consciousness. She was then sent to ER on 1/25/21  where evaluation work up was completed.  After initial episode of attacks, patient began to have episodes of nasal flaring, scrunching and locking of the mouth almost every day for one month. January 2021-February 2021. The nasal flaring and jaw symptoms lessened to weekly and then resolved in April/May 2021.   In July of 2021 these episodes/attacks began again consistently with stereotyped involuntary motor movements of whole body, spasticity in limbs, and tingling in nose/face lasting for a minimum of 20 minutes up to an hour. These attacks have caused extreme levels of anxiety, depression, stress and pain unable to complete her day to day tasks and career as she was able to prior. While patient is awake and alert throughout attacks, at times, she is unable to speak due to spasms in mouth causing locking of jaw. When symptoms heightened again in July, an ambulance was called and she was taken to the ER where she was given ativan and discharged home.  In September of 2021, patient was seen by neurologist, who diagnosed her with functional movement disorder. As stated in his detailed assessment,  patient's symptoms may be exacerbated by anxiety and stress triggers yet the actual cause of these attacks and episodes still remains completely unknown. As time progresses, these attacks cause brain and structural changes impacting wellness and optimal functioning.    Fast forward to present day, again it's OCTOBER- almost a year since the initial onset of symptoms requiring hospitalization. Patient has still been experiencing all of these symptoms as explained in depth above including but not limited to:  involuntary stereotyped joint/muscular tics and contractions, spasticity in hands, and stroke like symptoms with facial drooping and tingling of nose.    Prior to receiving the flu shot in January patient was a healthy, happy, functioning 27 year old independent female working, married,  and pursuing a degree in social work while teaching at a pre-school full time. These attacks are not patient's baseline and are are extremely debilitating to her physical, mental AND emotional well being. With the frequency and onset of these attacks almost daily every aspect of her life is impacted. At times she is unable to fulfill her role as a student and as an employee to the severity and intensity of these attacks. Patient was prescribed a muscle relaxant to alleviate pain levels for joint pain with the attacks yet these have an intensive sedating effect and are unrealistic for an individual to take regularly in order to function in society with a career and schooling.   Per neurology report, and testing completed thus far, the definitive cause of these attacks all are consistent with the administration of the influenza vaccination in January of 2021. With patient having no significant past medical history prior to the vaccination there is a high probability the vaccination triggered these attacks.   Patient referred to this writer (me) following initial OT evaluation at facility in September of 2021 for cognitive behavioral therapy treatment. Patient will continue for next 2 months to manage anxiety symptoms and stress levels from these episodes as they are severely impacting all aspects of her every day life and career currently as listed in depth above.  High accredited research studied have shown high correlation rates with flu vaccination and adverse side effects all consistent with patient's symptoms.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received Pfizer/BioTech COVID booster shot at approximately 12:30pm on 10/13/21.  Patient stated that right arm was slightly sore and that she experienced some mild hallucinations the same evening.  The next morning (10/14/21) she noticed what appeared to be an "X" on the right arm where the injection had been administered.  She thought it may have been a contact irritation (mentioned possibly a latex reaction) but I advised the patient that we only use non-latex bandages and nitrile gloves during administration of vaccines.  The patient continued to monitor the area which was warm to the touch, itchy and continued to grow in size.  She presented mid-day to the pharmacy on 10/17/21 to ask the pharmacist their professional opinion of what to do about the reaction.  The pharmacist advised the patient that the incident needed to be reported to VAERS for documentation but that the patient could treat the area locally with over the counter antihistamines (i.e. Benadryl, Claritin) and 1% Hydrocortisone.  I advised the patient to draw around the borders of the rash to monitor the response to the OTC treatments and that as a precaution she should follow up with her PCP Monday morning 10/18/21.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: From August 2020 through August 2021 ? I was able to run and lift weights in small doses for the first time since 2011. I had small relapses but it was the healthiest I have felt since 2011, when the drug Imunvoir cured me for 18 months.  Covid Vaccine Dose #1: Pfizer ? March 7 ? Fatigue for 4 days starting on Day 2. I felt completely normal after a week.  Covid Vaccine Dose #2: Pfizer ? August 18 ? Minor fatigue turned into intense body fatigue and body aches for the first 2.5 weeks.  Symptoms included headache and nausea.  I felt absolutely awful  On Day 18, I started a course of Prednisone ? 20 mg for 5 days.  My strength began to come back but my brain fog was still very intense.  My physical strength held up after the steroids but my energy would crash around 4 pm.  One month after the vaccine, I re-started Thymasin Alpha 1 daily and then added BPC 157 to 4 pills per day.  This was the regimen that I used in early 2020 that coincided with improvement. I also started Ketotifen, an antihistamine to combat possible Mast Cell issues.  Three days later on September 21, I woke up nauseous in the middle of the night and began several weeks of intense anxiety that I had not experience since early 2020.  I also began to experience very bad tinnitus in my ears. Toward the end of September 2021, the weakness in my body began to increase.  I stopped the Thymasin Alpha 1 and Ketotifen to see if there was a correlation. I cut the BPC 157 to twice per day.  October 5: My legs and arms felt so weak that they felt numb.  This was a new feeling for me and something I never experienced before.  It lasted about an hour.  The next day it happened again around 11 am, but this time it did not improve.    As I write this update on October 17, from morning until night, but body is incredibly weak and I feel absolutely awful. Sometimes it?s difficult for me to walk and sometimes my limbs feel so tired they feel numb.  My brain fog is intense and has limited my ability to function like a normal person.  The anxiety is okay, but the tinnitus in my ears is very loud.   It feels like every week my condition begins to worsen.
HISTORY: Chronic fatigue syndrome in remission for several years.
PRIOR_VAX: tdap - August 2019

One week after vaccination (10/15/21), patient started developing new swelling at the site of injection. Through 10/16 and 10/17 swelling turned red and painful and grew down arm and under arm. It is a continuous redness, and is not a rash.  Patient had no reaction at all up until 10/15/21.

Wednesday, Oct. 6, went to Urgent Care for rash. Prescribed Clotrimazole-betamethasone cream for fungal infection.   Thursday, Oct. 7, Pfizer COVID booster (both my husband and I received the same Lot # Pfizer vaccine). I used Clotrimazole-Betamethasone cream 3 times before booster. Two applications on Wednesday, Oct. 6, and one application day of booster. Also, I had never heard of not using Tylenol or Motrin before a COVID vaccination. I cannot remember if I might have been taking Tylenol for tooth discomfort after a dental implant September 1, 2021.  Friday, Oct. 8, mild discomfort. Took Tylenol.  Saturday Evening, Oct. 9, extreme reaction to what I believe to be the Pfizer booster. Symptoms appeared severely and suddenly. From my neck to my waist, front, sides, and back of my torso, what felt like piercing, debilitating muscle spasms with any extremely small movement. With movement, even breathing the wrong way, must have lasted only seconds but felt like minutes of torture. I do not remember my legs or arms having, for lack of a better word, spasms, but I could not put my leg on a small step stool without my husband?s help. Perhaps because the leg movement could not be achieved without some mid-body movement. I felt weakened to the point of not being able to perform the smallest task, but I think it was from the pain, not that my muscles could not move. When my husband helped me into bed Saturday evening, I could not budge, one way or the other, the physical suffering was too much. One other prominent symptom that appeared quickly, my right knee that had meniscus surgery several years ago ballooned with swelling.  Sunday, Oct. 10, misery. Continuation of Saturday evening symptoms. No relief. Tylenol and Motrin could not touch the pain.  Monday, Oct. 11, Dr. appointment with primary care physician. Doctor?s notes ?acute myalgia after COVID vaccination.?  RX, Prednisone, 20 mg, 3xday, for 5 days. After 2nd dose of Prednisone, symptoms began to dissipate quickly with each passing hour and day.   Sunday, Oct. 17, I feel fatigued and weakened, some joint stiffness in my left foot and right knee, however, pain is gone, and agony is over.   I hope my reporting can help in a small way to help advance COVID vaccines.
OTHER_MEDS: Clotrimazole-Betamethasone cream, Tylenol, PreserVision Areds 2, vitamins C, B12, D3, and Zinc
CUR_ILL: 9/1/2021,  Dental Implant, RX Amoxicillin, Tramadol-Acetaminohhin  10/6/2021, fungal infection

Patient received vaccine at 1530 on 10/15/21. At around 1630 on the same day, patient began having uncontrolled NBNB vomiting, diaphoresis, and central chest pain he attributed to heartburn. Of note, he has had this central chest pain for the previous week as well. His family was concerned about his vomiting and were worried about dehydration. He called the COVID vaccine hotline in early am of 10/16/21 and was referred to the ED. In the ED  he was found to have elevated troponin and 1 mm ST elevations in inferior leads with reciprocal depressions in V2 and V3. He was given aspirin, heparin, Zofran and transferred to a hospital for LHC. On presentation to  his CP was about a 6/10, after transfer to the cath lab, he was not having any pain.    LHC performed which showed 100% occlusion of RCA. DES x1 performed but unfortunately patient went into complete heart block with resulting hypoxia, tachycardia, and diaphoresis and diffuse rash. There was suspicion that part of plaque had embolized down the RCA. Patient was intubated for flash pulmonary edema and started on norepinephrine. RCA was again engaged and additional complex DESx3 performed. Repeat evaluation of left coronary vessels with IVUS reveals stenosis of left main.
LAB_DATA: EKG with 1 mm ST elevations in inferior leads with reciprocal depressions in V2 and V3. Troponin  100.87 on 10/16/21.
HISTORY: HTN HLD COPD Prior TIA GERD w/ Barrett's esophagus IBS w/ diarrhea Chronic pancreatitis Cervical stenosis

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At first, normal flu like symptoms and fatigue, low grade fever - like everyone else and to be expected for 24 hours and then that subsided.  Then shortly after within the same week of the vaccine I noticed subtle things like difficulty bringing my arm up to brush my teeth.  I could do it but it was like I was fighting my body to do so.  Symptoms increasingly got worse and more symptoms were noticed and they are as follows: Difficulty typing, difficulty writing, dizziness, difficulty walking - gait off and difficulty getting to a standing position, extreme weakness in my legs (had to stop driving), difficulty holding items and felt like I was going to drop things as I was very weak in my arms, chest pain, emotional extreme fatigue, I had a short bout of time of nauseau, uncomfortable/painful feeling in my chest...felt like things were swelling, my voice kept changing, waves of feeling like I was powering down, when I laid down...I would feel like I was going to pass out so I would sleep sitting up in a recliner, felt like I was in a fog, emotional and would cry over nothing (so not like me at all...typically a happy person), felt like my body was fighting me all the time.  This started as subtle signs and increasingly got worse with more and more signs and symptoms coming on for two months.  On July 7th, I took a nap in the afternoon and when I woke up I noticed a significant difference.  The dizziness was gone.  I continued over the next couple of weeks to slowly improve.  My doctor's were contributing this to low thyroid levels.  However, when I had the same reaction after the second Moderna vaccine I am thinking that perhaps it is a result of the vaccine.  I will submit a second document for my symptoms after the second vaccine.  I feel like my body over reacts after the vaccine and it exasperates signs and symptoms of my current medical issues (low thyroid symptoms and inflammatory condition as a result of having Covid in January of 2021) and in addition new symptoms show up such as the neurological issues as well.  When discussed with my doctor my thoughts on my body overreacting and this being a result of the vaccine, she too thought it is a possibility.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: For the first 24 hours, I experienced extreme fatigue, body aches, flu like symptoms but milder than experienced after the first dose.  On Monday 9/27, I noticed subtle neurological symptoms start just like after the first vaccine with difficulty putting my arm to my mouth when brushing my teeth.  It increasingly got worse on 9/28 and I was having difficulty writing, my gait was off, dizziness and light headed, my chest began to hurt (inflammatory condition symptoms), fatigue continued., feeling like I was powering down, when I laid down dizziness was worse and felt like I was going to pass out...had to sleep sitting up, extreme weakness in my arms and legs, difficulty getting from a sitting position to a standing position and when I do I have to try to get my balance before taking steps or I am afraid I am going to fall.  I thought about going to the ER  mainly because of the chest pain but I decided to take the ibuprofen to see if that would help with the chest pain and it did.  I did not have all of the same symptoms as last time, I had less symptoms this time and they were short lived.  I had the symptoms for a week and a half and then it all subsided leaving me with my normal low thyroid symptoms of weak legs and fatigue.  However, the inflammatory symptoms have continued to linger with coming and going in waves to this day.  The neurological symptoms subsided in a week and I slowly started to improve after that and after a week and a half, it seemed to be over.  It seems just like after the first vaccine, my symptoms of low thyroid and inflammatory condition are exasperated due to the vaccine and in addition neurological symptoms also start to occur after the vaccine.  I did not report this with the first vaccine because I did not contribute these symptoms to the vaccine at first.  I had no idea why this was happening to me.  Then, when I discussed it with both my primary doctor and my endocrinologist and the ER doctor...they all thought it was a result of low thyroid symptoms.  I missed my second dose due to being in the hospital and was hesitant to get my second dose but after talking to my endocrinologist again about my symptoms and whether she thought it was a result of low thyroid levels, she said yes.  I decided then I would get my second dose and then experienced the same symptoms after the second dose only not as severe and not as long of period of time.  I do believe that the vaccine exasperates my signs and symptoms of low thyroid levels, inflammatory condition and triggers neurological issues to occur.

Lost sight in eye from one stroke; Pressure in back of head and temples; Probably had 3 strokes, 2 of them were very close together; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of CEREBROVASCULAR ACCIDENT (Probably had 3 strokes, 2 of them were very close together), BLINDNESS (Lost sight in eye from one stroke) and HEAD DISCOMFORT (Pressure in back of head and temples) in an 81-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch nos. 014M20A and 030120A) for COVID-19 vaccination. On 24-Feb-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 02-Mar-2021, the patient experienced CEREBROVASCULAR ACCIDENT (Probably had 3 strokes, 2 of them were very close together) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and medically significant) and HEAD DISCOMFORT (Pressure in back of head and temples) (seriousness criterion hospitalization). On an unknown date, the patient experienced BLINDNESS (Lost sight in eye from one stroke) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and medically significant). The patient was hospitalized on 02-Mar-2021 due to BLINDNESS, CEREBROVASCULAR ACCIDENT and HEAD DISCOMFORT. At the time of the report, CEREBROVASCULAR ACCIDENT (Probably had 3 strokes, 2 of them were very close together), BLINDNESS (Lost sight in eye from one stroke) and HEAD DISCOMFORT (Pressure in back of head and temples) outcome was unknown.            Concomitant medications also included High blood pressure medication. No treatment medications were reported.  Company Comment: This case concerns a 81-year-old female patient with medical history of Neuropathy, Blood pressure high and Stroke (Stroke in eye) as well as history of polypharmacy, who experienced serious (hospitalization and AESI) unexpected events of cerebrovascular accident, blindness. The events occurred 6 days after the second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine). The rechallenge was not applicable. I have my birth control arm implant in my left arm. I asked the medical assistant if it will affect it. I was told it won't. I had a very sore arm that felt like it was going to fall off both times. I will be arranging an appointment with my doctor to discuss it. With both vaccines it felt like something travel in my body.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: BLOOD CLOT ATTACHED FROM THE LEFT KNEE UP TO STOMACH; This spontaneous report received from a patient concerned an 83 year old female. The patient's weight was 243 pounds, and height was 66 inches.  The patient's concurrent conditions included: severe arthritis, and sleep disorder. The patient had no known allergies. The patient did not have a family history of blood clot, nor did the patient travel recently and was not sitting around. The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin, and batch number were not reported, expiry: UNKNOWN) dose was not reported, 1 total administered to left arm on 03-MAY-2021 for prophylactic vaccination. The batch number was not reported and has been requested. Concomitant medications included trazodone for sleep, acetylsalicylic acid (aspirin), allopurinol, ascorbic acid (Vitamin C), colecalciferol (Vitamin D3), lisinopril, lovastatin, oxybutynin, ropinirole, verapamil, glucamide MSM and triamterene.  On an unspecified date several months ago, the patient experienced swollen left foot (toes to ankle) and she mentioned it to her physician who didn't say or do anything about the foot. The swelling remained persistent and she mentioned it to her primary care doctor (PCP) several times, yet testing was not done at the time. She stated that the foot was painful and a little bit red. She noted that the pain in her foot and ankle was dull and present even when she was sitting and it became very painful when she was standing or walking. The patient stated that she had to use a cane due to the pain. On AUG-2021, the patient had her whole left leg, from thigh down to toes got swollen and when the swelling worsened, she went back to the physician. On an unspecified date in SEP-2021, the patient underwent an Ultrasound and reported that it showed no blood clot. The redness in the foot had also spread to her entire left leg. The patient performed therapy and exercises at her home, she was icing, elevating the leg and wearing compression stockings to help relieve the swelling. None of these interventions helped so the patient went back to her physician who referred her to a Spine Specialist. The patient had a spinal x-ray and pelvic/abdominal CT scan done, both test results were normal except severe arthritis was shown in X-ray, although this was previously diagnosed.  On 12-OCT-2021, the patient consulted a vascular doctor who performed an in-depth ultrasound of both legs and stomach. She was told about the results, that a blood clot was attached and has been there a while, from the left knee up to her stomach. The patient was started on Xarelto 15 mg twice a day. It was reported that on the 22nd day of treatment, the dose of Xarelto will be reduced to 20 mg once per day. The patient reported that she started experiencing a sharp pain in her knee which comes and goes especially when she is walking or standing. The patient reported that she has an ultrasound scheduled for next Tuesday and would have weekly ultrasounds to monitor the progress.  The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient had not recovered from blood clot attached from the left knee up to stomach. This report was serious (Other Medically Important Condition).; Sender's Comments: V0:20211028558-COVID-19 VACCINE AD26.COV2.S- Blood clot attached from the left knee up to stomach. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hospitalized 10/11/2021; COVID-19 positive 10/11/2021; fully vaccinated  Assessment/Plan    DIAGNOSIS at time of disposition: 1. COVID-19  2. Acute respiratory failure with hypoxia   ED Disposition    ED Disposition   Hospitalized   MEDICAL DECISION MAKING Patient presents to the emergency department with concern for nausea and loss of appetite which is been progressive over the last several weeks, especially worse in the last 3 days.  It at triage patient was noted to be saturating 86% on room air.  She was placed on 2 L nasal cannula and improved to 93%.  Of note patient is not on home oxygen.  Her physical exam is remarkable for a fatigued appearing elderly woman, with crackles across the lung fields bilaterally.  Differential diagnosis includes but is not limited to viral versus bacterial pneumonia, pancreatitis, biliary pathology.  IV access was established she was given 1 L of IV fluids for hydration given reports of poor oral intake, as well as Zofran for nausea. EKG is obtained which does not demonstrate peaked T-waves, evidence of ischemia, or right axis deviation.  No significant changes when compared to EKG from 08/04/2021. Patient has a workup which is significant for positive COVID-19 PCR. Patient is a CT thorax which shows findings consistent with a viral pneumonia, no evidence of underlying bacterial process.  Given patient's hypoxia on room air as well as her tachypnea, she will be admitted to the hospitalist service for continued management.  Patient did not have clinical deterioration while in the emergency department. 10/13/2021 note: ASSESSMENT / PLAN:  Patient is an 83 year old female with CAD status post stenting in 2005, type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, hypertriglyceridemia, and CKD who presented with approximately one month of fatigue and malaise as well as progressive shortness of breath, loss of appetite, and diarrhea. She was found to be COVID-19 positive, despite being fully vaccinated. #COVID-19 pneumonia CT thorax showed peripheral areas of ground glass opacities, consistent with COVID-19 pneumonia. Procalcitonin 0.37, have low suspicion for superimposed bacterial pneumonia, especially given no focal consolidation on imaging. Exact date of symptom onset difficult to ascertain; therefore, is outside the window for remdesivir. National shortage of tocilizumab currently.  Plan:  - Continue dexamethasone 6mg daily x10 days total or until discharge. - Tessalon perles for cough. - Supplemental oxygen therapy as needed 10/15/2021 note: ASSESSMENT / PLAN:  Patient is an 83 year old female with CAD status post stent placement in 2005, type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, hypertriglyceridemia, and CKD who presented with 3-4 weeks of fatigue and malaise as well as progressive shortness of breath, loss of appetite, and diarrhea. She was found to be COVID-19 positive. Her oxygen requirements have been relatively stable; however, she has been intermittently disoriented and agitated, requiring PRN Zyprexa.  #COVID-19 pneumonia Patient's oxygen requirements have been stable to improving. She was on 70% FiO2/50 L/min on high flow nasal cannula at the time of my exam.  Plan: - Continue dexamethasone 6mg daily x10 days total or until discharge. - Supplemental oxygen therapy as needed. - Tessalon perles for cough.  #Hypoxia Most likely secondary to COVID-19 pneumonia, which appeared worse on CTA 10/13 compared to imaging on 10/11. Low suspicion for PE, given no evidence of PE on CTA. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Vaccine given was expired, it had expired on 9/21/2021

He got his vaccine, as soon as he got it he got a stiff neck.  The next day he got a headache, an then really sick to his stomach and took Pepto Bismol and went to get out of his chair on Monday following the vaccine and he fell to the ground and had excruciating pain in his left leg and back, which he has never had this problem before. Everything is on the left side.  He then got a big huge blister on his elbow, which is starting to heal up.   He went to the ER twice, he went to his PCP and his endocrinologist and received steroids, muscle relaxants which did not help.  He cannot recline back as the pain is excruciating and has not slept in his bed since 9/13/21.   The pain is starting to subside, just a little bit, it is now a 7/10 now, but was a 10/10, and he cannot do anything as he now has to walk with a walker, which he did not need a walker before the vaccine.    He had a regular appointment with his PCP today who was shocked to see the blister on his arm.     He saw an orthopedist and they have him scheduled for an MRI on 10/28/21 of his spine.   His endocrinologist sent him for COVID testing and also for Lyme testing and they both came back negative.     The doctors that he has seen cannot figure out what or why he is having these symptoms.    He feels that this is reaction to the vaccine.  He did in the past had elbow and shoulder surgery on the left side 34 years ago and never had a problem, and feels that it has attacked his weak spots from previous surgeries.   He has a few friends that are now in wheelchairs from the same vaccine.    He also has blisters on his little finger and his ring finger on his right hand, and the doctor said that it was deep and that he had never seen one that deep.  The skin has been healing and was extremely thick and that it took half of his knuckle off of that hand, which is the only thing that has happened on the right side.
LAB_DATA: One set of blood work and his white blood count is up, which they told him is some sort of infection, and they want to do another test in 2 weeks to compare them.

Immediately after receiving the shot at 10am, I felt flushed and had pain at injection site. this lasted for an hour or so and slowly faded into a dull aching in my arm and general fatigue throughout my body over the course of the next 8 hrs. I attempted to go for a walk after work about 6pm and noticed I was having irregular heartbeat with some rapid heart rate . I stopped walking because of these symptoms and drove home. I continued to feel tired with periodic rapid heart rate until bedtime. I got into bed about 10:15pm and by 10:30 pm I began a full onslaught of symptoms: I was flushed, fever of 102 F, I was sweating and shaking uncontrollably with chills and constant teeth chattering. I sweat through 2 frozen ice packs, had extreme dizziness when sitting up, weakness in arms and hands and legs. I could not take myself to toilet, needed assistance with transferring, toileting and drinking a glass of water. My neck and temples were throbbing in the veins causing a tremendous headache. I could not sleep  but was afraid to take any medication for how it might react . My husband assisted me in getting water every 30 mins or so. The chills/shaking lasted until about 4 am. At 630am I had to get up for work, so I took OTC ibuprofen which did help my headache. My fever dropped down to 99 F as well by mid day on 10/15. Over the last three days I continue to hover about 1 degree above regular body temperature and still feel very fatigued with a headache that only subsides with routine dosing of ibuprofen. Most concerning, I am continuing to have cycles of irregular heart beat with rapid heart beat and the sensation of a "skipped beat".
ALLERGIES: lactose intolerance, sensitivities to animal products and gluten

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Saturday, 07/30/2021, I started feeling a sore throat, fever, upper respiratory symptoms. The next night, 07/31/2021, I tested positive for Covid via a BinaxNow home test.  These results were confirmed through Urgent Care via a PCR nasal swab test on Sunday, 08/01/2021.  My fever ran off and on for 10 days, my upper respiratory symptoms were very severe - shortness of breath, coughing, stuffiness, severe bronchitis-type symptoms making it difficult to lay down without coughing.  I had a sore throat for 3 days and headaches off and on for 4-5 days, beginning 07/31/2021.  I suffered with fatigue, insomnia, and lack of physical stamina.  The worst of my symptoms did not abate for 14 days and on day 16, I started coughing up blood with mucus from my lungs  My doctor then ordered a CT scan (with contrast) to ensure I did not have blood clots in my lungs or pneumonia because I had been sick/coughing for so long.  I was negative for both blood clots and pneumonia and was given a steroid inhaler to assist with my breathing.  The shortness of breath/fatigue/lack of physical stamina continued for nearly 2 months, after testing positive for Covid-19 on 07/31/2021.  I went from being very physically active before contracting Covid (with no breathing issues) to being unable to even shower without feeling winded, post Covid.
LAB_DATA: BinaxNow at-home Covid nasal swab test (07/31/2021), PCR nasal swab test (08/01/2021), CT Scan w/Contrast (08/11/2021)
OTHER_MEDS: Compounded Progesterone, Armour Thyroid, Levothyroxine, Potassium Citrate ER, Chlorthalidone, Metformin ER, Phytomulti Vitamins, Mag Glycinate, Ortho Biotic, KForce, Omegas (860 EPA/580 DHA), Trifalomin, and Meta I3C
CUR_ILL: Diagnosed mild upper respiratory infection 1 week prior (tested negative for Covid at that time)
ALLERGIES: Slight sensitivity to Demerol, Rash allergy to Macrobid

Autonomic function test done in 9/2021 shows signs suggestive for POTS and autonomic dysfunction of sympathetic sudomotor fibers. Possible in small fiber or autonomic neuropathy.
LAB_DATA: Date of Study: 9/24/2021 Autonomic Testing  Reason for study: Question small fiber or autonomic neuropathy; postural orthostasis Heart rate, deep breathing: Normal heart rate variability for age with the average difference of 5 cycles being 19 beats per minute. Valsalva maneuver: Normal Valsalva ratio of 1.9. Normal blood pressure response to the Valsalva maneuver. Tilt study: 5 minutes of continuous blood pressure and heart rate monitoring were performed with the patient in a supine position. Thereafter, the patient was elevated to a 70� heads up tilt position for 10 minutes, then subsequently returned to a supine position for an additional 5 minutes of recording. The baseline heart rate fluctuated between 90-95 bpm, increasing to 120-125 bpm during the tilt. There was no associated change in blood pressure. Quantitative sweat test: Reduced total sweat production from the proximal leg and distal leg.  Normal total sweat production from the forearm and foot sites. Clinical correlation: Abnormal autonomic studies, reflecting dysfunction of the sympathetic sudomotor fibers. Additionally, the tilt examination is abnormal, with a pattern suggestive of the postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome.  Of note, such findings can be seen within the context of a small fiber or autonomic neuropathy.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: So what happened was, on Sunday Sept 5th my youngest daughter woke up with a fever of 103 F and a runny nose. On Thursday Sept 2 I had to go to the OB on call at the hospital because I was having a lot of Bronchitis symptoms. They treated me with antibiotics, so I went on that. While still on the antibiotics, on the 8th of September I woke up with congestion, body aches, no fever, muscles and bones hurting and I had a cough I think, a mild one. I had a lot of post nasal drip drainage going on at that time. Then, the symptoms persisted and then when I woke up on Sept. 10th 2021 and I could not smell or taste anymore. Then over the weekend I was still not feeling well and having trouble breathing so I took my albuterol inhaler. On Monday, the 13th I got the antibody treatment. On Sept 14th I felt a little better and by Friday the 17th I felt a bit better. I was finally cleared for end of isolation on Sept. 19th 2021, I was definitely better but no taste and smell still and a lot of drainage. Maybe by the 24th of Sept I was feeling a lot better but still no taste and smell, the smell came back on Oct 1st, but very minimal and fluctuated. By now, 10/18/2021 it is better but the lack of taste and smell is still there, it is subdued and goes in and out throughout the day. So for my pregnancies, I have had some miscarriages but I have never had any of these symptoms. I have three daughters with no complications in their births. Right now I am 29 weeks, my date of delivery will be 1/02/2022.

I am a 63-year-old woman, who was in good health with no preexisting conditions.  I took the first injection Moderna COVID19 vaccine shot on Friday. September 24, 2021 due to the mandate to keep my job as a substitute teacher.  I started feeling bad and my breathing deteriorated each day to the point where I was out of breath.  On Wednesday, September 29, 2021, I went to urgent care.   After initial check-up, they called the ambulance and I was transported to the Emergency Room and immediately placed on high flow oxygen.  One more day delay and I would have died due to lack of oxygen. At the hospital, on Thursday, September 30, 2021, the doctor removed ONE Liter (Quart) of fluid from my right lung, the next day the doctor removed ONE and ONE THIRD liters of fluid from my left lung.  The fluid was a rusty reddish color.   At the hospital, all kinds to tests were performed, heart test, cancer test, COVID19 test and bacterial tests, all results were negative.  By Saturday, I was off oxygen and was released from the hospital on Monday, October 4, 2021.  By the end of the week, I again started feeling out of breath.  On Monday, October 11, the doctor ordered a chest X-ray.  The x-ray was read on Tuesday morning.  The Doctor immediately called me and told me to go to Emergency Room at Medical Center.  On Wednesday, October 13, 2021, surgery was performed on me to install draining tubes from both of my lungs.  More than a liter of fluid was removed from each of my lungs.  Again, more tests were performed on me to find the root cause and none were found.  On Friday, October 15, I was released from the hospital with tubes from my lungs.    On Sunday, October 17, 2021, the visiting nurse came to my house and drained 25 ml from my right lung and 75 ml from my left lung. The nurse is scheduled to come three times a week to remove the fluid. Per ED Note: 62-year-old male presents to the emergency department with shortness of breath, body aches, and headache.  He states that he tested positive for Covid infection on Wednesday.  He also complains of fevers and chills.  He denies any associated chest pain.  He denies any lower extremity pain or swelling.  He denies history of DVT/PE.  He does state that he is a liver and kidney transplant patient.  He does state that he received both Pfizer vaccine doses  62-year-old male presents to the emergency department with fever, shortness of breath, body aches, headache, and COVID-19 infection.  The patient was found to be hypoxic on room air at 86%.  He was placed on 2 L supplemental oxygen which improved his saturation into the upper 90s.  A chest x-ray and laboratory analyses were ordered for further evaluation.   The patient's chest x-ray revealed bilateral infiltrates consistent with Covid pneumonia.  His laboratory analyses revealed a lymphopenia in addition to hypomagnesemia.  His magnesium was replaced with 2 g of IV magnesium sulfate.  His BUN and creatinine were also slightly elevated consistent with dehydration.   The patient will be admitted to the internal medicine service with infectious disease on consultation.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: She got her vaccine, her arm was sore, she started feeling the pain on the left side of her shoulder, but it wasn't strong.  She started at about 2:00 started to experience a slight headache and started to feel nauseous.  Then, she took some Tylenol 650 ES and she was able to sleep for a few hours.  When she woke up in the morning the headaches were getting worse as well as the nausea.  She started feeling weak and the pain on the left side had spread throughout her body and felt like she was coming down with a cold.  She read the instructions that she was given including the symptoms which was the flu-like symptoms, etc, so she felt that she was going to have this for a few days.  By mid-afternoon the headaches were getting even worse and still feeling weak and taking Tylenol and resting.  By early evening about 5-6 she started vomiting and by that time she was very weak.  She was shivering with chills, had a fever and cold sweats and the headaches were even worse.  She did her best not to go to the hospital.  She was like this for a few days and continued to vomit and was loosing weight and was only on fluids due to the vomiting.  This continued for 2 weeks, and had some periods were it was not so bad.  After about a month she called her doctors office and scheduled an appointment as she was so weak and could not keep food down and still having the severe headaches.  When she went to the doctor he informed her not to take the 2nd vaccine, and he sent her home and told her if it continued to see him again or go to the ER.  He told her to see her neurologist for the headaches.  She went to see her neurologist the next day who gave her magnesium intravenously, nerve block injections and explained to him that this was since 4/4/21.  The following day she called him back as the nerve block and IV did not help as she was still weak and vomiting.  She then called her PCP who told her to go to the hospital where she was admitted.  She was given IV's.  By that time when they weighed her she had lost 8#.  She was in the hospital for 7 days and they finally submitted.  When she was discharged she was still having nausea but she was feeling better, she was still having headaches, but not as severe.  She waited so long as she felt that it was going to get better.  When she was discharged she was still weak, still had the body aches, was not feeling like herself, and she did not have much appetite.  She was having days about once a week or two weeks that she would vomit and continued with the nausea even with her favorite foods. She is a worship leader and was very busy with her church and had to take a leave as she was not able to sing and her throat was hurting a lot, which she contributed to the vomiting.  She then scheduled to see a specialist, allergist who specialized in voice.  She then had a scope done and he told her that she would not be able to sing for about a month and put her on medication.  She was informed that due to the vomiting that she developed reflux which was in her voicebox, and also laryngitis.  She also had periods when she would loose her voice completely.  He put her on two different medications and continued to see him until she was better.  When she last saw him she was told that the reflux was better, but her VM was still not right.    She used to walk a lot, which is her choice of her exercise and now since the vaccine she can only walk 5 blocks and cannot due to the fatigue.    She has tired that she is tired and can just sleep for long periods of time and lethargic.   She also continues to have the headaches are mild, but different from her migraine headaches and feels that they are due to the vaccine.   She does get migraines and has been admitted in the past as they have to be treated intravenously.  Usually the magnesium and the nerve blocks work but not always.  They headaches now come and go.
OTHER_MEDS: Prednisone, hydroxychloroquine, Brea inhaler, Albuterol as needed.  Essential 1 vitamin.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: History per chart review and husband. The patient is a 55 Years-old Female with a history of rheumatoid arthritis, anxiety/depression, overweight who presented with acute shortness of breath. 2 weeks prior to admission she filled her routine prescription for hydroxychloroquine for her rheumatoid arthritis, however husband reports that she stopped taking this and started taking a supplement from another country called RT King and reported improvement in arthritis symptoms.  She also had congestion and sore throat around this time and tested herself for Covid with a home test that was negative. Shortly after this she was performing her job as a provider for patient that passed away from Covid and attended the funeral.  On 9/8 she reported difficulty breathing and pain in the chest and back with deep breaths.  This spontaneously resolved.  Then on 9/9 in the evening she had fever, body aches, however she attributed this to her rheumatoid arthritis and the storm pressure changes.  9/12 she felt great then played at the beach with her grandkids running around.  Then 9/12 in the evening she felt ill and took a home Covid test that was positive.  Husband took a home Covid test that was negative.  She did not initiate any outpatient care other than Mucinex and vitamin C.  9/13 in the morning she had difficulty breathing, hyperventilating, blue lips, diffuse body pain, feeling very weak to stand.  She was not drinking or caring for herself.  She was able to walk to the truck.  Her family brought her to the ER freestanding.  At the freestanding ER, she had initiated and tested positive for flu and negative for Covid by antigens.  Covid PCR later returned negative.  She was transferred to the main ER and desaturated during the transport and stopped breathing.  She maintained a pulse.  In the ER she was intubated.  Pressors Were Started to Maintain MAP. CTA was negative for PE, however ED physician and family practice physician clinically suspected PE and that there could be multiple small thrombi in the lungs rather than a large PE detectable by CTA.  She was started on heparin drip.  ICU accepted the patient and began management. She tested negative for COVID IgM antibodies and positive for COVID IgG antibodies. She devloped DIC (disseminated intravascular coagulation) and TTP (thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura). During the hospital course she had sputum and blood cultures positive for streptoccocus pneumonia. She later had pseudomonas VAP and Enterococcus faecalis bacteremia. She had failure of lungs, liver, and kidneys. She was treated with maximal critical care management including broad spectrum antibiotics, ventilation, continuous renal replacement therapy, blood/platelet transfusions, chest tube, OG tube feedings, and anticoagulation initially that was later discontinued. She had minimal responsiveness to pain only after sedation withdrawal and was unable to breath spontaneously. On 10/9 the family agreed to palliative vent withdrawal and she expired. I suspect her severe illness may have occured due to abrupt discontinuation of hydroxychloroquine for rheumatoid arthritis and antibody dependent enhancement of influenza due to COVID vaccine.
LAB_DATA: CTA 9/13 showed  No CT angiographic evidence of pulmonary embolus is seen. There are bilateral lower lung subsegmental atelectasis. Mild bilateral pulmonary infiltrates are seen.

Client presented to clinic for Janssen's COVID-19 vaccine with her husband. Client appeared anxious and had multiple questions about the safety and efficacy of the vaccine prior to administration. Client stated she was being required to have the vaccine and was not happy about it and was very nervous. Client cried briefly and reported that her heart rate felt 'fast' due to anxiety. Client ceased crying, reported that her questions were answered, and consented to the vaccine. COVID-19 Janssen was administered at 10:25am. At 10:28am, client reported feeling dizzy, lightheaded, nauseous and was visibly pale and diaphoretic. Client was lowered safely to the ground with the help of her husband. Within 20 seconds, the client began to feel better and pallor had diminished. Client reported that she had passed out during a blood draw previously, but never problems with vaccine. Client slowly resumed a sitting position and returned to a chair. Client declined juice, but drank water and reported feeling much better. At about 10:38, client again felt faint, was pale and diaphoretic and was lowered to the ground. Client stated that the muscles in her neck, near her throat, felt tight, but anxiety related. Client denied problems breathing or sensation of swelling in throat or mouth. No hives were present. Client was given a cold compress, snack and juice and reported that the tight muscles in her neck had gone away. Client reported feeling better and resumed sitting in chair. Client was making conversation, but at about 10:55am, client reported feeling faint and was moved to the ground. At this time, additional nursing staff were called in. Client reported that the tightness in her neck had returned and she was still feeling lightheaded. Client denied symptoms of anaphylaxis, reported no problems breathing. Informed the client's husband that we advised EMS services due to delayed recovery. The client began to cry and shake uncontrollably. Monitored the client on the ground while we called 911 at 11:00am. EMS arrived at 11:05am and assessed the client for about 15 minutes. Vital signs and EKG were all normal. No signs of anaphylaxis. Client continued to feel dizzy, appeared diaphoretic and pale, and could not stop shaking. Client was advised to seek medical treatment as a precaution and to be monitored. Client was unable to stand unassisted due to lightheadedness when standing. Client was transported via ambulance to Hospital.

Patient began recording blood pressure readings with home monitor following initial visit to clinic. SYMPTOM_TEXT: May 10th, 103+ fever and signs of dehydration observed out of nowhere.  Watched into the evening, with worsening conditions, took to ER by 7am on May 11th.  Went from fully functioning adult to sudden and complete muscle loss within 24 hour period.  No control over motor functions, unable to walk, talk, stand on own.  Watched in ER for almost 10 hours, ran several tests but couldn't determine anything, diagnosed with dehydration and fatigue and sent home that evening, told to alternate Tylenol and IBprofen to reduce fever, rest and return if symptoms not better after 7 days.   Fever of 103 persisted, no muscle control persisted, could barely walk to restroom, sit to eat minimal food and by May 18th took back to hospital as 103+ fever was still persisting.   After more blood tests, chest x-rays, and monitoring, decided to admit to hospital as slight infection was observed in prostate.  Fluids given, more tests, and more aspirin/IBprofen but not much change in symptoms.  By May 20th, discharged from hospital with 21 day antibiotics (for prostate inflammation/ possible infection) and physical therapy prescribed at home.   Fever began to dissipate after an additional 10 days on antibiotics and muscle control returned slightly after the first 4 sessions of physical therapy (2 weeks).  Took an additional 2 weeks of physical therapy, daily exercise routine, and mostly sleeping all day to gain any motor control back and begin to feel even a little stronger.  By mid-June, able to walk half way around the block and by mid-August able to walk around the block 2x a day.  Prior to these events, walked routinely all day with no issues.
LAB_DATA: May 11th - chest xray, May 18- blood and hospital admission, fluids, May 19 - xrays, blood work, hospital care, May 20 - blood work, discharge, May 27 - June 17 - in home physical therapy
HISTORY: Cardiovascular heart monitoring, but no events in last 20 years Prostate inflammation monitoring, but no events in last 2 years

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After first shot, pt experienced sore neck and back, and while these were expected reactions to the shot I told her to contact her clinic if concerned. Later, she called reporting trouble breathing and neck swelling so I told her to get seen. Her symptoms resolved without needing care, she ended up canceling her inhaler. After discussing with her provider, she was given the OK to get second dose from us on 06/22/21.   The day after the dose (06/23/21) she said she experienced a full month of feeling fatigued, trouble breathing, and weakness. She ended up doing a telehealth visit with her primary on 07/21/21 and provider said it could have been a covid infection that was present before the vaccine was administered.  She was prescribed prednisone and inhaler and symptoms gradually resolved. She got her Flu shot with us on 10/07/21 without issue. Because of scarcity of information it is difficult to determine with certainty but this is more likely a case of covid infection that set in before vaccination, rather than an adverse reaction to the vaccine.
LAB_DATA: Date unknown, but pt got covid test in late July (over 1 month after the vaccination and onset of symptoms) and it was negative. However, husband became ill before date of pt's second shot and his test came back positive later, after pt was already showing symptoms post-vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I woke up feeling like I was in a Fog around 0530. I felt drugged and sedated. I work in an inpatient Pharmacy, that morning I worked in the sterile IV room. I reported to work at 0630. I told me coworkers how I felt. They asked me if I should be working, I told them I was fine. As the morning progressed my mind grew more frenzied, more sporadic. I spiraled, I couldn't maintain thought patterns, I couldn't think straight. As 0800 came, I knew that there was a strong possibility that I could make some mistakes and took a break and sat down in the hospital library. It didn't help. I grew more frantic and foggy. Around 1100 I left work, my coworkers asked me if I was ok to drive. I told her I was fine, it was only two and a half miles to home. I shouldn't have driven. I drove frantic that I was going to crash and sure that someone was in my blind spot as i switched lanes. I got home safely, kicked off my shoes, took a Xanax that I have prescribed for Panic attacks ( Since i had been fighting one off for about 4 hours at that point) and fell into bed, where i stayed in the same position for 5 hours, by 2000 that night I was still feeling foggy, but the anxiety was still there, though not as severe.   It is now Monday after the test and I still feel elevated anxiety levels, though less of the fog. If I had not had the xanax at home I would have admitted myself to the ER.
PRIOR_VAX: TDAP/ Feb 2019/ swelling and welt at injection site

I got up from bed, it was 1 AM, and I started feeling very dizzy. My walls looked like they were moving and I definitely knew something was off. I checked my blood pressure at home and it was showing 205/110. I checked it three times and received the same result (general range). I went to the hospital ER, where they checked my blood pressure and confirmed that my blood pressure was elevated. I was given clonidine 1/10 mg every 6 hours as needed. My cardiologist gave me Bystolic (Beta Blocker). I took both medications for about three months before my blood pressure returned to normal range. I was taken off clonidine and Bystolic, but continued with olmesartan medoxomil.
LAB_DATA: I had my blood pressure checked at the hospital. It was verified that my blood pressure was elevated 190/100.
CUR_ILL: I was not experiencing any illness.

Hospitalized 10/9/2021; COVID-19 positive 10/9/2021; fully vaccinated  BRIEF OVERVIEW: Discharge Provider: DO Primary Care Provider at Discharge: MD Admission Date: 10/9/2021 Discharge Date: 10/13/2021 DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY:   HOSPITAL COURSE: Patient is an 86 y.o. female with past medical history of RA on prednisone, DM II, HTN, hypothyroidism, and remote hx of right sided breast cancer who lives with her husband at independent living facility. Patient presented to the ED with chief complaint of generalized weakness and cough. She was subsequently found to be positive for COVID-19. Vaccinated in Feb 2021. Upon arrival to the ED, the patient was afebrile, hypertensive 196/83 and hypoxic to 87% on room air requiring 2L oxygen. She was admitted for acute hypoxic respiratory insufficiency secondary to COVID 19 pneumonia. She was started on decadron to complete a 10 day course. Also found to have a Klebsiella UTI for which she received Rocephin x 3 days then was restarted on home prophylaxis macrobid. Given generalized weakness, multifactorial but likely due to concurrent infections, therapy recommended subacute rehab. She improved throughout her hospitalization and therapies changed recommendation to home with therapies. She was seen by pulmonary rehab and discharged on 2L oxygen around the clock. She was also set up with the COVID at home program to continue to monitor her closely at home. She was discharged home in stable condition. She was instructed to restart her home prednisone once she completes her course of decadron.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Around the end of August 31, 2021- bilaterally my salivary gland lymph nodes were swollen but not painful and firm, hard. It may have been going on longer than that, but I was not paying attention and it was not painful. 09/07/2021 in the morning, at my dentist appointment for my regular cleaning, the  dentist was concerned there was excessive swelling or fullness in the neck region. He said there was an unusual fullness and that I should contact my primary care doctor. 09/14/2021 at 08:00 AM, I saw my primary care doctor, he referred me to have an ultrasound on my head and neck region on 09/23/2021. The results were abnormal. Lymph nodes were enlarged on both sides, bilaterally enlarged on both sides. The primary doctor referred me on 9/29/2021 @ 9:15, for a CT of the  neck with IV contrast. The results were bilateral abnormality of tissues of numerous enlarged lymph nodes. I saw the ENT 10/14/2021 @ 08:00 AM - seems to me the swelling had gone down, but lymph nodes were presumably still enlarged. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was very wobbly walking and the morning after the vaccine (Pfizer Booster shot and regular Flu Shot) and my wife had to assist me to get to the bathroom.  As I finished urinating, I could not stay standing and didn't fall but went down to the floor by the toilet and could not get up.  I could not even crawl to get out of the bathroom. I had extreme fatigue caused by trying to get up.  It was like all my strength was gone.  I called for my wife and she assisted me to crawl out of the bathroom but only made it to the door.  After resting awhile (15 minutes), with much difficulty, my wife assisted me to get up into a rolling desk chair.  I stayed in the chair for a few hours after she rolled me to my desk where I could do some work at the computer but it was really hard to sit up.  After this time, I was able to stand and walk very carefully to my regular easy chair.  I stayed there the rest of the day.  The rest helped and I was able to walk but it was pretty unsteady.  I went to bed about 10pm and when I woke up, I felt much better and could walk but I tired easily. Each day after this incident things have gotten better and better.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: October 2 - Around midnight, he was making a slow cooked beef braised in wine (tomatoes and wine) - it took hours - he went to check it and I didn't want to eat it that late at night because I can be sensitive. He brings a small plate - I had a few bites. I start to feel, shortly after, severe pain in my upper stomach that went through right through to my back. I had some water. The pain gets worse. And it starts to spread to one side of my body. I started walking around to help it feel better; it got worse. I start to feel heartrate went up and I start to feel out of breath and agitated. I was fine before I ate something. It kept getting worse no matter what I tried to do. I could feel it in my back and in my jaw and in my arm. I had my husband to call the Medical center. - Ambulance (he had to stay with our son at home). My pulse is through the roof and my heart rate was higher than 140 (on our oximeter). My blood pressure was 200. They took me to the hospital - they did heart tests.
LAB_DATA: heart tests, bloodwork, ultrasound of upper right quadrant; they do complete blood count and heart blood work and liver enzymes and all the major organs. Every thing came back negative. As I'm sitting in ER for 7 hours with no water or anything. My bowels have rested for 7 solid hours in ER. They gave me a "gastric cocktail" - Pepto Bismul with lidocaine. That really didn't do much. IV - Pepcid - gave me that. I felt somewhat better. I didn't leave the hospital feeling great - I still had pain but not as much as when I went to ER. I followed up with my doctor. And doctor wants me to do colonoscopy and endoscopy test - to see if there is something in stomach and intestines. My primary care doctor was seen Tuesday of last week - Dr - I told her these things and I also told her that my place of employment totally shut down during COVID and I gained 30 lbs over the course of it and I have had to homeschool my kids. I have issues with sleep and with pain in my joints. I have had emotional and psychological issues. I have low energy. My stomach is bloated etc. Vit D Deficiency; H Pylori test (breath test) - Gave me the blood work for those things. I was positive for H Pylori; my Vit B12 was so low if it was off the shots I received a Vit B12 shot   - and will get one every month. And I was low in Vit D and am taking  a supplement for that - slow release Vit D that for once week.  Two antibiotics - Omeprazole and Antacid - four pills in the morning and in the evening for two weeks - to kills the bacteria in my intestinal lining and intestines. Since starting the treatment: My energy is up; my stomach isn't bloated; I have lost 4 pounds in a week. I have less pains. I am walking in the evenings and trying to get my joints moving. I am having less aching in my joints with the walking. I am not as cloudy in the head.  I had tolerated my two COVID shots pretty well with the immediate symptoms. Still in process of recovering.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I gained a great deal of weight during COVID. On June 13, during an extreme heat wave and being on my feet for a long period of time, I experienced severe swelling in my left foot and less so in my calf, which progressed until July 9th, and spread to my right lower leg to a lesser degree. I went to the ER to rue out a DVT. After Well's Criteria and an ultrasound, a DVT was ruled out. Swelling gradually receded slowly within the next two months. In September, I experienced severe pain and swelling in both hands, with significant numbness and tingling in all of my finger tips. It was my perception that the swelling went from my legs to my hands. After seeking medical attention and referral for ultrasounds by a vascular surgeon to r/o vascular insufficiency, it was determined that lymphedema was the diagnosis of exclusion. I have been going to PT for 4-5  treatments so far. The swelling has receded but the numbing and tingling persists. I am wearing compression gloves during the day as much as I can (my job requires that I wash my hands frequently between patients) and carpal tunnel splints during the night with the gloves underneath.
LAB_DATA: Wells Criteria  rheumatoid factor numerous ultrasounds CBC  BMP

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After the second Moderna shot I had three days of chills and fever. Once that was done I noticed small painful red dots around my eyes that would get worse then subside. I thought it was eczema so I put moisturizer on it but it didn't go away. Then about a month after the second shot I felt terrible again and had another day of fever and chills. I went and got a covid test which was negative. Then in the beginning of July I once again had fever and chills. I also had pain and itching in my vagina which I thought was a yeast infection. The fever wasn't going away so I went to an urgent care and was diagnosed with a UTI. I began the antibiotics but my fever was getting worse so I went to the ER. It turned out to be a herpes outbreak, the first I ever had. That's what was causing the fever and chills. When I started taking the Valtrex the rash that had still been around my eyes finally went away. I believe that the rash was also herpes. I have been taking Valtrex since July and the herpes in my vagina and inside my upper and lower lips in my mouth is still there. It no longer hurts but I can see the raised strips of skin in my mouth and the red streaks in my vagina. It feels like this is never going away and I am worried about getting the Moderna booster in case it would make it all flare up  even worse than it is now.
LAB_DATA: HSV detected by rapid screen. Herpes Simplex Virus Type 1 isolated test confirmed by Fluorescent Monoclonal Antibody Staining

Client reported to EMT feeling "hot" while in the observation area. EMT escorted the client outside into the courtyard to cool down. RN responded and noted the client seated outside without her mask on. The client reported feeling "hot, nauseous, and like my left eye is closing." RN noted no swelling over the client's left eye. Pupils were equal round and reactive bilaterally. EMT provided the client with an emesis bag. RN recommended the client move inside onto the anti-gravity chair. The client agreed, ambulated unassisted with a steady gait into the observation area and sat in the anti-gravity chair in a high fowler's position. Vitals obtained at 7:37 PM were as follows: BP 148/96, HR 90, and O2 96%. The client reported a history of high blood pressure. She takes Lisinopril and Hydrochlorothiazide daily, and states she took her medications this morning. The client has a history of blurry vision, nausea, vomiting, and dizziness after taking Gabapentin. The client stated her current symptoms felt different than the symptoms she experienced after taking Gabapentin. The client has a history of blood shot eyes after utilizing a steroid inhaler. Lastly, the client reported flu-like symptoms after a previous flu vaccine that lasted a few weeks. The client had equal strength bilaterally in her upper and lower extremities. At 7:44 PM the client drank water and was provided an ice pack. The client placed the ice pack on the back of her neck. Repeat vitals obtained at 7:45 PM were as follows: BP 151/93, HR 96, O2 97%. The client stated she last ate chicken soup at 4:00 PM. At 7:46 PM the client stated her nausea had improved and that her eye "feels calm." At 7:51 PM the client reported "feeling tingling from the knee down" bilaterally. RN noted  2+ pedal pulses bilaterally. Sensation was intact to touch over her feet bilaterally. The client denied any itching. Repeat vitals at 7:53 PM were as follows: BP 143/91, HR 86, O2 97%. The client stated she was, "feeling better. The tingling is moving up my leg." RN did not visualize any signs of redness or rash on the clients ankles bilaterally or near the vaccine administration site. At 7:56 PM the client stated she was, "not feeling warm anymore." Repeat vitals obtained at 8:00 PM were as follows: BP 139/94, HR 86, O2 97%. The client stated she "feels much better." Repeat vitals obtained at 8:05PM were as follows: BP 147/88, HR 86, O2 97%. RN provided education regarding s/s of anaphylaxis, when to seek EMS, and to follow up with her doctor regarding her blood pressure. The client voiced understanding of this education. The client stood up without assistance at 8:08 PM and denied any dizziness. The client stated the tingling was "much better" and stated "I feel fine." The client was accompanied by her son, who was going to drive her home. The client ambulated unassisted out of the observation area at 8:08 PM.
ALLERGIES: The client has a history of blurry vision, nausea, vomiting, and dizziness after taking Gabapentin. The client has a history of blood shot eyes after utilizing a steroid inhaler. Lastly, the client reported flu-like symptoms after a previous flu vaccine that lasted a few weeks.

Patient came in for the 1st dose of Moderna vaccine. Patient was asked to wait 30 minutes as she had a history of shortness of breath due to allergy to naproxen. Patient immediately stated that she had a strange taste after the vaccine was given. I sat in the booth with the patient for the 1st 10 minutes to monitored her. During that time she also described feeling suddenly fatigued/weak. I kept asking if she had any signs of anaphylaxis (shortness of breath, swelling of the month tongue or throat) which she denied. At 12 minutes of observation she rejoined her family at the post observation area and was continued to be monitored. Once her 30 minutes was up she stated that she still felt weak and had a strange taste and she stated that upon simple physical exertion (walking to the allergy aisle from the post observation area) she became short of breath. I did administer a dose of benadryl and and let her know if her if her shortness of breath becomes worsens I have an Epi Pen to administer and I could call emergency services. She declined me calling for emergency services and stated she would just go home and rest. I did give her a dose of Benadryl in the pharmacy and she purchased another bottle of Benadryl to take home, and she said she had Tylenol at home. I did call her again at 7PM just to check on how she was doing. Her husband said that she had been sleeping since she got home. I explained that could be a side effect of the Benadryl but the vaccination can also cause fatigue. Her husband confirmed that she did not have any worsen symptoms but was going to give her tylenol to combat any potential feve

SYMPTOM_TEXT: terrible rash, initially on his legs; in the beginning it started out as "hives"; has left scarring from where he had itched (scratched).; describe the rash as red; describe the rash like "a poison ivy and mosquito bite itching; Scratching; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of rash in a 65-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. The patient received a dose of Shingrix in left arm and experienced a terrible rash that he has had for 3 months and it progressively got worse after the second shot. At the time of reporting, the rash was more concentrated on his upper torso, chest, arms, and on his back were his lats (latissimus dorsi) are. Rash was not resolved. Concomitant products included METOPROLOL, LISINOPRIL, ACETYLSALICYLIC ACID (ASPIRIN (E.C.)), OMEPRAZOLE, CALCIUM CARBONATE, COLECALCIFEROL (VITAMIN D 2000), DULOXETINE, FOLIC ACID, VITAMIN A NOS, BALOFLOXACIN, VITAMIN B12 NOS (VITAMIN B 12 [VITAMIN B12 NOS]) and AMLODIPINE for an unknown indication.    On 25-Feb-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 26-Feb-2021, the patient experienced PRURITUS (rash and itching all over the trunk) and RASH (got rash and pruritus all over the trunk). On 28-Feb-2021, the patient experienced BELL'S PALSY (Bells palsy) (seriousness criterion medically significant) and ORAL HERPES (fever blisters). The patient was treated with PREDNISONE for Adverse event, at a dose of 15 milligram and VALACYCLOVIR [VALACICLOVIR] for Adverse event, at a dose of 1 gram. On 27-Feb-2021, PRURITUS (rash and itching all over the trunk) and RASH (got rash and pruritus all over the trunk) had resolved. At the time of the report, BELL'S PALSY (Bells palsy) and ORAL HERPES (fever blisters) outcome was unknown.        The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown.   For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments. This case involves a 35-year-old female subject with the medical history of eclampsia who experienced the non-serious unexpected adverse events of palpitations, heart rate irregular, somnolence, malaise, headache after her first vaccination with mRNA-1273 and product administration interrupted at the scheduled time of her second dose due to unavailability of the vaccine. After having received her second vaccination dose, she once again experienced palpitations (positive re-challenge).  Pregnancy exposure was also reported without any information on the date of LMP and pregnancy status.  The benefit-risk relationship of mRNA-1273 is not affected by this report.   This case was linked to MOD-2021-336369.
